### Computed Properties

Computed properties are reactive values derived from other data. They are cached based on their dependencies and only re-evaluate when dependencies change.

```vue
<script>
export default {
  data() {
    return {
      firstName: 'John',
      lastName: 'Doe'
    }
  },
  computed: {
    fullName() {
      return `${this.firstName} ${this.lastName}`
    }
  }
}
</script>
<template>
  <p>{{ fullName }}</p>
</template>
```

### Computed vs Methods

- **Computed**: Cached, only re-evaluated when dependencies change
- **Methods**: Re-executed on every render

### Computed Setter

Computed properties are read-only by default. You can define a setter:

```js
computed: {
  fullName: {
    get() {
      return `${this.firstName} ${this.lastName}`
    },
    set(newValue) {
      [this.firstName, this.lastName] = newValue.split(' ')
    }
  }
}
```

### Watchers

Watchers observe a reactive value and perform side effects when it changes:

```vue
<script>
export default {
  data() {
    return { question: '', answer: '' }
  },
  watch: {
    question(newVal, oldVal) {
      if (newVal.includes('?')) {
        this.answer = 'Thinking...'
      }
    }
  }
}
</script>
```

### Deep and Immediate Watchers

```js
watch: {
  user: {
    handler(newVal) {
      console.log('User changed', newVal)
    },
    deep: true,
    immediate: true
  }
}
```

### watchEffect

`watchEffect` automatically tracks any reactive dependencies accessed inside it:

```js
import { watchEffect } from 'vue'

watchEffect(() => {
  localStorage.setItem('count', this.count)
})
```
